==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trist
<hw>Trist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Tryst</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Trust.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A post, or station, in hunting.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A secret meeting, or the place of such meeting; a
tryst. See <er>Tryst</er>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>George Douglas caused a <qex>trist</qex> to be set between him and
the cardinal and four lords; at the which <qex>trist</qex> he and the
cardinal agreed finally.</q> <rj><qau>Letter dated Sept.,
1543.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trist</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Trist
<hw>Trist</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>triste</ets>, L.
<ets>tristis</ets>.]</ety> <def>Sad; sorrowful; gloomy.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Fairfax.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Triste</ent>⟦br⟧
